				<td colspan="2"><span class="postbody"></span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Mr.Parsalin wrote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">I just refinanced my home. Went from a 30 year 7% apr to a 15 year 3.74 apr. My payment went up a whole 7 dollars a month. GO ME!!</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />
I'm not going to comment on the rest (though it was a nice post), but actually something very similar to this came up in my economics class when I took it a few years ago.  It showed both the payment difference and  the total money paid difference between 25, 20, and 15 year mortgages on a house (250k I think, though it doesn't really matter).
<br />

<br />
Basically, by taking it to 15 years, your payments are more in the range of something like $50 a month, but your total payment is less by something like 100k (or more).  These numbers could be WAY off, but the savings was amazing.
<br />

<br />
Basically the idea was to get as short a term as you can afford, even if it means taking less of a dwelling, since you'll pay it off WAY faster, and have WAY more money in the end.<br />_________________<br />Eriol Telcontar
<br />
Arch Convoker - Master of the Orb
<br />
The Tribunal</span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
